e history of Anglo-Indian relations in the early Chesapeake and New England in a broad transatlantic context while drawing parallels with subsequent efforts by England as well as its imperial rivals—the French, Dutch, and Spanish—to plant colonies in America. Dominion and Civility promises to broaden our understanding of the exchange between Europeans and Indians and makes an important contribution to the emerging history of the English Atlantic world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aColonial administratorszUnited StatesxHistoryxSources. 0aIndians of North AmericaxGovernment relationsyTo 1789. 0aIndians of North AmericazChesapeake Bay Region (Md. and Va.)xHistoryvSources. 0aIndians of North AmericazNew EnglandxHistoryxSources. 0aIndians, Treatment ofzChesapeake Bay Region (Md. and Va.). 0aIndians, Treatment ofzNew England. 4aEarly American & Colonial History. 4aU.S. History. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172925640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501729256423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501729256/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK